# 🔍 Kubernetes Upgrade Readiness Assessor

> A CLI tool that combines **deterministic kubectl analysis** and **LLM-powered reasoning** to assess whether a Kubernetes cluster is safely upgradeable — before you touch production.

[![Python 3.8+](https://img.shields.io/badge/python-3.8+-blue.svg)](https://www.python.org/)
[![kubectl](https://img.shields.io/badge/kubectl-required-lightgrey.svg)](https://kubernetes.io/docs/tasks/tools/)
[![OpenRouter](https://img.shields.io/badge/LLM-OpenRouter-orange.svg)](https://openrouter.ai)

---

## 💡 Why this tool?

Production Kubernetes upgrades are risky. A wrong upgrade can:

- **Remove APIs** your workloads depend on → immediate outage
- **Break admission webhooks** → block all deployments cluster-wide
- **Introduce CRD incompatibilities** → operators stop reconciling silently

Existing tools like **Pluto** or **kubent** only check deprecated APIs.  
This tool goes further by combining **live cluster inspection** with **LLM expert reasoning** to surface operator compatibility issues, failure scenarios, and a structured remediation plan.

---

## ⚡ Quick Start

```bash
# 1. Install dependency
pip install requests

# 2. Set your OpenRouter API key (free tier available at openrouter.ai)
export OPENROUTER_API_KEY=sk-or-xxxxxxxxxxxxxxxx   # Linux / macOS / Git Bash
$env:OPENROUTER_API_KEY="sk-or-xxxxxxxxxxxxxxxx"   # Windows PowerShell

# 3. Run the assessment
python kube_assessor.py -s 1.34 -t 1.35 -o report.md
```

**Output:**
```
============================================================
  Kubernetes Upgrade Readiness Assessor
  1.34 → 1.35
============================================================

Collecting cluster state...
  [1/15] kubectl version
  [2/15] kubectl get nodes
  ...
Running static analysis...
  Removed APIs    : 0
  Deprecated APIs : 0
  CRDs            : 6
  Webhooks        : 2
  Readiness Score : 60/100
  Confidence      : 95%

Calling LLM (OpenRouter)...
Generating report...

✅ Report written to: report.md
```

