## 🧪 Test Cluster Setup

This project was developed and tested on a local kind cluster:

```bash
# Create cluster
kind create cluster --name k8s-1.34 --image kindest/node:v1.34.3

# Install cert-manager (adds 6 CRDs + 2 webhooks)
kubectl apply -f https://github.com/cert-manager/cert-manager/releases/download/v1.14.0/cert-manager.yaml

# Install metrics-server (with kind patch for insecure TLS)
kubectl apply -f https://github.com/kubernetes-sigs/metrics-server/releases/latest/download/components.yaml
kubectl patch deployment metrics-server -n kube-system \
  --type='json' \
  -p='[{"op":"add","path":"/spec/template/spec/containers/0/args/-","value":"--kubelet-insecure-tls"}]'
```

---

## ⚙️ CI/CD Integration

A GitHub Actions workflow is included at `.github/workflows/k8s-upgrade-assessment.yml`.

It connects to any existing cluster via a kubeconfig stored as a GitHub secret, runs the assessment, publishes the report as a job summary, archives it as a downloadable artifact, and **fails the pipeline if the decision is NOT RECOMMENDED** — acting as a quality gate before any upgrade.

```
GitHub Actions runner
       │
       │  kubectl (via KUBECONFIG secret)
       ▼
  Your Kubernetes cluster  ←── real cluster, not a fresh one
       │
       ▼
  kube_assessor.py → report.md → artifact + job summary
```

**Setup:**
```
GitHub repo → Settings → Secrets and variables → Actions
  KUBECONFIG          ← contents of ~/.kube/config
  OPENROUTER_API_KEY  ← your sk-or-... key
```

